Boott Cotton Mills Museum
Dont miss the roar of a 1920s weave room with operating power looms! The museum also includes exhibits and video programs about the Industrial Revolution, labor and the rise, fall, and rebirth of Lowell.
Adults, $4.00; Youths, 6-16 
Also at the museum, check for daily happenings at the Tsongas Industrial History Center, Boott Gallery, New England Folklife Center, Lowell Historical Society, and shop at the Museum Store.
Boott Discovery Trail
Discover the story of Lowells mills, their machinery, and their workers during your visit to the Boott Cotton Mills Museum.
Children of all ages can pick up their work aprons and time cards at the museum entrance and through hands-on activities explore how cloth was made from raw cotton to finished cloth.
Try your hand at carding, spinning, drawing-in, and weaving.
Experience the roar of a 1920s weave room and learn what working in a textile mill was like.
Available during regular museum hours.
Free with museum entrance.
Become a Junior Ranger
During your visit to Lowell National Historical Park pick up a Junior Ranger Activity Booklet at either the Visitor Center or the Boott Cotton Mills Museum.
As you explore the park, complete the series of activities presented in the booklet.
Return it to a ranger at the desk before you leave and become a Junior Ranger - badge, certificate, and all! Answers to the activities can be found throughout the park.
Free.
Boott Cotton Mills Museum Hours October - November 25, 2001 Open Daily, 9:30 a.m. - 5:00 p.m.; Museum Talks at 2:15 p.m. and 3:15 p.m.; Weave Room Talks each Saturday at 12:00 noon
November 26 - March 31, 2002 Open 9:30 a.m. - 4:30 p.m., Monday-Saturday, 11:00 a.m. - 4:30 p.m., Sunday, Museum Talks at 2:15 p.m. and 3:15 p.m., Weave Room Talks Saturday at 12:00 noon
April 1 - May 24, 2002 Open Daily 9:30 a.m. - 5:00 p.m.; Museum Talks at 2:15 p.m. and 3:15 p.m., Weave Room Talks Saturday at 12:00 noon.
For Teachers:
Building America's Industrial Revolution: The Boott Cotton Mills of Lowell, Massachusetts __________________________________________________________________
Working People Exhibit
Explore the history of "mill girls" and immigrants in a Boott Mill boardinghouse.
The Working People Exhibit, located in the Patrick J. Mogan Cultural Center, tells the human story of the Industrial Revolution by concentrating on the working people of Lowell.
Join a park ranger for a 10-15 minute Museum Talk--scheduled throughout the day.
Learn more about "mill girls," immigrants, and life outside of work.
Working People Exhibit Hours October - November 25, 2001 Open Daily, 1:00 p.m. - 5:00 p.m.; Museum Talks at 1:30 p.m., 2:30 p.m. and 3:30 p.m.
November 26 - March 31, 2002 Open Daily 1:00 p.m. - 4:30 p.m., Museum Talks at 1:30, 2:30 
April 1 - May 24, 2002 Open Daily 1:00 p.m. - 5:00 p.m. Museum Talks at 1:30, 2:30 
MOGAN CULTURAL CENTER COMMUNITY EXHIBIT Dance Traditions of Southeast Asia Enduring Symbols of Cambodia and Laos
This new exhibit chronicles the history, ritual functions, and modern-day culture of traditional dance from Cambodia and Laos.
The exhibit features a collection of beautiful dance images from the early 20th century through the present plus a stunning array of costumes, masks, dance artifacts, and props.
Also on display in the gallery is "Ancient Steps on American Soil, Cambodian Dance in Lowell," a photography exhibit of the Angkor Dance Troupe by Andrew Page of Portland, Maine.
Also at the Patrick J. Mogan Cultural Center: On the first Sunday of every month beginning in November, the Angkor Dance Troupe will offer the public an intimate, behind-the-scenes look at Cambodian dance in the making with open rehearsals from 2:00 to 4:00 PM. Angkor recently moved its rehearsal operation into the third floor of the Patrick J. Mogan Center through a cooperative agreement with the Lowell National Historical Park.
